{
  "doc_id": "58299",
  "text": "Histologic data from human PD brains has demonstrated increased Cox-2 immunoreactivity within both microglia and neurons of the substantia nigra suggesting that Cox-2-dependent prostaglandin production contributes to inflammatory gliosis and neuron death [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . A role for Cox-2 dependent inflammation and cell death in disease is supported by the MPTP toxin model of PD in which Cox-2 activity is required for the observed neuronal death [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Although a myriad of mechanisms are feasible, one intriguing idea is that the increased Cox-2 activity leads to dopamine oxidation and subsequent α-synuclein accumulation as Lewy bodies [CITATION_6] . We now extend this data to demonstrate that α-synuclein over-expression of particularly the missense mutant forms increased microglial Cox-2 expression.",
